Let's not forget the importance of staying informed and prepared for heatwaves in the future. Stay updated on weather forecasts, follow heat safety guidelines, and be proactive in adapting to the changing climate. #HeatandtheFuture

Homes with basements tend to stay cooler during hot weather. When searching or a new home or considering renovations, consider the benefits of a basement as a naturally cooler space during heatwaves. It can provide a retreat from extreme temperatures. #HeatandtheFuture

Heat and drought often go hand in hand. When preparing for the future, it's crucial to recognize the connection between these two factors and develop strategies to address both. Conservation and water management become even more critical. #HeatandtheFuture #DroughtAwareness

Wooded areas can offer natural shade and help mitigate the effects of heat. Consider spending time in parks or forests during hot days to enjoy cooler temperatures and take advantage of nature's air conditioning. #HeatandtheFuture #NatureCooling

As temperatures continue to rise, moving to cooler regions, especially towards the north, may become a viable option for escaping extreme heat. Keep in mind the potential environmental impact and plan accordingly. #HeatandtheFuture #ClimateMigration

Clothing choices matter in the heat. Opt for light-colored and loose-fitting clothes that allow air circulation. Consider wearing ice vests or cooling accessories to stay comfortable when temperatures soar. #HeatSafety #StayCool

Technology can help us cope with the heat. Fans and air conditioning can provide relief and help lower the risk of heat-related illnesses. Use these cooling methods to create a safer and more comfortable environment. #HeatSafety

Staying safe in the heat means finding shade and limiting strenuous outdoor activities during peak hours. Protect yourself by scheduling outdoor exercise for cooler parts of the day or considering indoor alternatives. #HeatSafety

🌡️ SECTION THREE: HEAT SAFETY 🌡️ Explore practical ways to stay safe during extreme heat, including seeking shade, adjusting exercise routines, and leveraging cooling technologies like fans and air conditioning. We'll also discuss the importance of appropriate clothing choices.

Heat stroke or heat exhaustion can occur more quickly than you might think. In extreme heat, it may take only 15-30 minutes for these conditions to develop. Stay vigilant and seek medical attention if you or someone around you shows symptoms. #HeatandHumans

Vulnerable populations such as the elderly, children, and those with chronic illnesses are particularly susceptible to the negative effects of heat. Check on your loved ones during extreme heat events and ensure they have proper cooling measures in place. #HeatandHumans

Heat affects our bodies in various ways. It can lead to dehydration, heat cramps, heat exhaustion, and even heat stroke if not addressed. Stay hydrated and be aware of the signs of heat-related illnesses. #HeatandHumans

🌡️ SECTION TWO: HEAT and Humans 🌡️ Discover how heat affects our bodies, particularly the vulnerable, and the timeline for heat stroke and heat exhaustion. We'll also delve into the impact of wet bulb temperature on human health.

Wet bulb temperature is an important measure of heat and humidity combined. It indicates how effectively our bodies can cool down through sweating. When the wet bulb temperature rises too high, it becomes extremely challenging for our bodies to regulate heat. #HeatUnderstanding

Climate change has caused a significant rise in temperatures over the past 20 years. It's crucial to recognize the connection between climate change and the increased frequency and intensity of heatwaves. We need to take action to combat this issue. #HeatUnderstanding

When heat, humidity, and direct sunlight come together, it can be a dangerous combination. It intensifies the heat's impact on our bodies and increases the risk of heat-related illnesses. Stay protected and seek shade when possible. #HeatUnderstanding
Heat and humidity go hand in hand. Humidity makes it harder for our bodies to cool down through sweat evaporation, making us feel hotter and more uncomfortable. #HeatUnderstanding

@ShoemakerJess Excited to dig in!

By humbly and respectfully widening our scholarly attention, we discover an array of active land reform initiatives that deserve greater care and concern. Understanding these projects can inform how we all reimagine the future and build a better world together.

I’d love feedback on the essay. The main point for Twitter is this: There is a lot going on in contemporary Indigenous land systems. These are not archaic, isolated relics of some memorialized past, but active, living, and often-conflicted systems of complex property relations.
More obnoxious self-promotion, this time about Indigenous land reform projects in Canada: https://t.co/V0kVRKBJ5k)

In the essay, I also summarize some important work being done in Canada where First Nations and others are negotiating new land-governance authorities with mixed success. (Thankful again to @FulbrightCanada for the year to work around and learn with these efforts.)
For more on this theme (and a side of shameless self-promotion), see also:  https://t.co/3sGxmTxzdq

In the essay, I give a couple of concrete examples. Rosser’s Navajo case study, for example, speaks to the difficulty of actually implementing land-tenure reform and underlines that, although law change is needed, grassroots action, imagination, and persistence is the real key.

Paying (careful, respectful, humble) attention to the diverse systems of Indigenous land tenure and governance that already operate across North America is critical not only for accurate understanding of existing property-system dynamics but also to see our full future potential.
America’s property system is already pluralistic and dynamic, but property scholars tend to focus on only a narrow swath of cases, experiences, and legal sources.

This argument is not unique - @yunpovi, for example, collects these themes much more expansively in her article "The Other American Law" - but I try to extend it here to the very specific political and legal project of future property reforms.  https://t.co/cyNDei6Vcm

Rosser's book takes us deep into a specific case study of the Navajo Nation’s struggle with exactly this kind of project, and in the essay, I argue that property scholars ignore these and other contemporary Indigenous property experiences to our collective detriment.

As I say in the essay: “We live in a world built from former worlds, and the residue of those ancestral structures, however ancient, continues to shape what we see and imagine, even as we march toward new land relations and continue a collective effort to make new maps.”

There’s growing consensus that many of our existing property rules and structures are unsustainable and, at times, outright harmful. But how does property change occur when the world we see is already so deeply rooted with tradition, experience, and law?
Big thanks also due at the outset to @EzraRosser, whose new book, A Nation Within: Navajo Land and Economic Development, is the inspiration for the symposium and the essay: https://t.co/eSRhgZkKyF
First, the essay – Land Reform in the Fifth World – is forthcoming as part of a Southwestern Law Review symposium (thanks wonderful editors!) and currently available here: https://t.co/RA6rQXVn5u

The evaluation questions are produced in the Finnish context but may be applicable elsewhere as well.In Finland, the new Climate Act requires policymakers to assess justice impacts of climate policies. This report aims to help the development of such evaluation.

To promote procedural justice in climate policy, assessing and dismantling constraints affecting participation is central.The justice impacts must be monitored and communicated in an open and accessible manner.

The relevance of various sociocultural backgrounds and vulnerabilities to the justice effects of climate policy must be recognized and accounted for better than previously.The role of minorities and the rights of future generations and indigenous peoples need special attention.

When evaluating distributive justice, attention must be paid to the distribution of benefits and disadvantages in society.If there is significant harm, compensatory mechanisms should be considered — but in a manner that upholds the steering effect of climate policy.

Evaluation questions presented in the report can be utilized for developing the evaluation of justice of climate policies.The dimensions of justice, and the evaluation questions derived from them, are intertwined. https://t.co/8I3otzEk0y

Evaluating climate policy justice should utilize the three dimensions of justice: distributive, recognition, and procedural justice. Evaluation also requires examining impacts at spatial and temporal scales.Fundamental and human rights help to define a minimum level of justice. https://t.co/tqHLB1Ayu7

The starting point for just climate policy is global and intergenerational justice. Failure in mitigating and adapting to climate change creates injustices.Comprehensive evaluation of justice impacts is crucial for making informed decisions and preventing conflicts.

7/Anyone with a crypto wallet can buy and retire tokenized carbon credits on the blockchainFor personal emissions, you can use an online calculator (ie https://t.co/PNyncvQyHF) to estimate your own carbon footprint, and retire credits that cover this amount, or more ✨

6/Novel technology helps: Carbon market transactions and retirements can be executed and recorded with blockchain technology 💻All transactions "on-chain" are publicly visible. This provides transparency & traceability - both key to building trust in carbon markets 🔍

5/Retiring carbon credits is therefore critical for achieving net-zero emissionsBut because carbon markets are currently notoriously intransparent, it can be challenging to verify if a credit has actually been retired, or just resold 🛒

4/BUT: To achieve net-zero emissions, purchasing credits isn't enough. The credits must also be → retiredWhen the retirement happens, the tonne of carbon that the credit represents is permanently removed from market circulation ✅

3/Organizations or individuals purchase these issued carbon credits in order to take responsibility for their carbon footprint 👣 and to support projects that benefit the climate and local communities 👨‍👨‍👧‍👧

2/Carbon credits are developed by low-carbon projects. These could be:🌞 Renewable energy installations👨‍🚒 Energy efficiency improvements🌳 Forest conservationThe timeline from project planning to finally issuing carbon credits usually spans around 5 years

1/Before we look at retirements, let's step back a bit and answer a key question: What actually is a carbon credit?A carbon credit represents one tonne of carbon dioxide that has been prevented from entering or is removed from the atmosphere 🏞️

7/7 Global warming can trigger local cooling. While it may seem contradictory, understanding the complex web of climate dynamics reveals the surprising twists and turns of our planet's changing climate. Mother Nature certainly loves to keep us guessing! 🌍❄️ #ClimateConundrum

6/7 Ice, ice, baby! Melting ice caps can contribute to local cooling. When glaciers and ice sheets melt, they release fresh water into the surrounding oceans. This influx of cold water can lower temperatures in nearby regions. A chilly surprise! 🥶❄️ #CoolWaterEffect

5/7 The dynamic duo: ocean upwelling and coastal fog. Climate change can intensify upwelling, which brings deep, cold water to the surface. As a result, coastal areas can experience foggy and chilly conditions. Time to invest in fog lights and cozy scarves! 🌁❄️ #ChillingCoasts

4/7 Changes in wind patterns can alter how temperature is distributed across the globe. A shift in wind patterns can bring cold air from polar regions to areas that used to enjoy warmer breezes. Suddenly, "it's getting hot in here" becomes "it's getting cold in here"🌪️#WindyWoes

3/7 🌨️ Snowy mountains, anyone? Climate change can increase snowfall in higher elevations. So while it may feel counterintuitive, some mountain regions are actually getting cooler due to heavier snowfall. Time to embrace skiing, folks! 🏂❄️ #SkiToSurvive

2/7 🌬️ Meet the chilling culprit: changing ocean currents! These powerful underwater highways can influence regional climates. When they shift, they can carry colder water to certain shores, making locals reach for their extra sweaters. Brrrr! 🌊❄️ #ThermalTraffic

1/7 🌡️ It's like nature's version of hot and cold! While the overall global temperature is rising, regional variations in climate patterns can cause certain areas to experience cooling. Talk about throwing us a climate curveball! 🌍❄️ #ClimateSurprises

ML algorithms are being used to analyze data from sensors and other sources to improve the efficiency of carbon capture processes. E.g., AI can be used to predict the flow of carbon dioxide and other gases through pipelines, helping to optimize the capture & storage process.

By analyzing data on waste generation and disposal, AI can identify patterns and suggest ways to reduce waste and increase recycling. For example, AI can analyze data on the types of waste being generated and suggest ways to reduce waste in the first place.
By analyzing data on traffic patterns and road conditions, AI can suggest alternative routes to drivers (Google Maps), reducing the amount of time they spend idling in traffic.

Precision agriculture uses AI to analyze data on soil moisture, temperature, and other variables to optimize agricultural practices such as irrigation and fertilizer use. This allows farmers to use resources more efficiently, reducing waste and increasing yields.

AI can improve climate modeling in a number of ways. For example, machine learning algorithms can be used to process large amounts of data, allowing us to better understand the complex interactions between different components of the Earth’s system.

One example of AI-powered smart grids is the EnergyHub platform, which uses machine learning to optimize the use of solar panels and batteries. EnergyHub uses real-time data to predict energy demand and adjust the output of solar panels and batteries accordingly.

By implementing strategies such as climate-resilient crop varieties, carbon sequestration, reducing GHG emissions, and embracing agroforestry, we can build resilient farming systems.

In conclusion, climate-smart agriculture practices are of utmost importance in mitigating the impacts of climate change, enhancing agricultural productivity, and ensuring the sustainability of our food systems.
By adopting CSA practices, farmers can enhance their resilience to climate shocks, access new markets for climate-friendly products, and improve their long-term profitability.
Socio-economic considerations: Climate-smart agriculture isn't just about environmental sustainability; it also aims to improve farmers' livelihoods and economic viability.

Water management:As climate change leads to altered rainfall patterns, effective water management becomes crucial in CSA.Practices like drip irrigation, rainwater harvesting, & water-efficient irrigation systems can help optimize water use, reduce vulnerability to droughts.
By diversifying farming systems, farmers can enhance ecological resilience, support pollinators, and promote overall sustainability.

Agroforestry and biodiversity conservation:Agroforestry, the integration of trees with crops or livestock, plays a vital role in CSA.Trees provide numerous benefits such as shade, windbreaks, and additional income sources.
CSA approaches include implementing improved livestock management techniques, optimizing nutrient application, and adopting precision agriculture technologies to minimize emissions.

Reducing greenhouse gas emissions(GHG):CSA practices also focus on reducing GHG emissions associated with agricultural activities.Agriculture is a significant contributor to GHG emissions, primarily through methane  from livestock and nitrous oxide  from fertilizer use.

This can be achieved through practices like conservation agriculture, which involves minimizing soil disturbance, maintaining soil cover, & diversifying crop rotations.By sequestering carbon, farmers contribute to mitigating climate change while improving soil health & fertility

Carbon sequestration:Another essential aspect of CSA is the promotion of carbon sequestration in agricultural soils.Carbon sequestration involves capturing atmospheric carbon dioxide (CO2) and storing it in soil organic matter.

These are cultivars specifically bred or selected to withstand the challenges associated with climate change, such as drought, heat stress, and pests.By planting resilient crops, farmers can enhance their ability to adapt to changing climatic conditions & maintain stable yields

It encompasses various practices aimed at mitigating the impacts of climate change and increasing agricultural resilience.Climate-resilient crop varieties: One important strategy in CSA is the use of climate-resilient crop varieties.
